<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="352" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1255,1749]" pageId="23" pageNumber="352">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,369,1255,1280]" pageId="23" pageNumber="352">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
This species has deeply excised mandible with the tooth forming an oblique angle (see Pitts 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="352">et al</emphasis>
. 2009: Fig. 45), lacks of mesosternal processes, has the marginal cell shorter than the stigma, has the first segment of the metasoma petiolate with the second segment, and has the genitalia with a short cylindrical cuspis (see Pitts 
<emphasis box="[260,309,1364,1388]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="352">et al</emphasis>
. 2009: 
<figureCitation box="[393,462,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1452,1474]" captionTargetBox="[265,1321,266,1418]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[251,1336,247,1430]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Odontophotopsis dalyi, sp. nov., 1. habitus; 2. head, frontal view; 3. mesosternum; and 4. pygidium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/892297/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="352">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
